All semiconducting properties of materials, such as the free-carrier concentration, flat-band potential, energy levels, and conductivity type, are critical components that lead to better device performance. These properties can be determined from a Mott–Schottky (M–S) plot consisting of the space-charge-layer capacitance (CSC) inverse square versus the bias potential50. It is well defined that the slope of such plot is used to determine the semiconductor doping density ND, and extrapolation of intercept may be used to compare the flat band potential Vfb, Fig. 5, using the well-known Mott–Schottky relation (Eq. 2):21CSC2=2ε0εreNDV-Vfb-KTe\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{{C_{SC}^{2} }} = \frac{2}{{\varepsilon_{0} \varepsilon_{r } eN_{D} }}\left( {V - V_{fb} - \frac{KT}{e} } \right)$$\end{document}which ND, e, ε0, εr, Vfb, and V are carrier concentration, electron charge, vacuum permittivity, the dielectric constant of semiconductor, flat band potential, and applied potential, respectively. T is the temperature of the operation (300 K), K is the Boltzmann’s constant (1.38 × 10−23 J/K), and CSC is the space charge capacitance. In this work dielectric constant for In2S3 films is equal to 8.5. As Mott–Schottky plot depicts (Fig. 5), the positive slope of the curves indicates that films all have an n-type conductivity51.Figure 5
